---
import BlogPostLayout from '../../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
import { getBlogPost } from '../../lib/blog-posts';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import ChatVsApi from '../../components/ChatVsApi';
import TokenBudget from '../../components/TokenBudget';

export const frontmatter = {
  title: 'How LLMs Actually Work',
  description: 'The short, jargon-free primer to send anyone who does not get how LLMs work: it is input to output, not a conversation.',
  author: 'Adelphi Liong',
  date: '2026-06-21',
  topic: 'tech' as const,
  tags: ['llm', 'ai', 'explainer', 'context'],
  shareMessage: 'Send this to anyone who does not get how LLMs work',
};
const post = getBlogPost('how-llms-work')!;
---

<BlogPostLayout post={post}>
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-4 mb-6">It is not a conversation</h2>
  <p class="mb-6">
    The first thing to unlearn is the word <em>chat</em>. It feels like you are talking to something. You are not. A
    language model does exactly one thing: you hand it an <strong>input</strong> (a big blob of text), and it hands back
    an <strong>output</strong> (more text). That is the whole machine. Input goes in, output comes out, and then it
    forgets you exist.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    So where does the "conversation" come from? The chat window is a <strong>view</strong> — a friendly picture painted
    on top. Under the hood, there is no running session keeping track of you. Every single time you hit send, the app
    quietly rebuilds the <em>entire</em> conversation from scratch — your first message, the model's first reply, your
    second message, all of it — plus a hidden block of instructions you never see, and re-sends the whole thing as one
    fresh input. The model reads it all, answers once, and forgets again.
  </p>

  <ChatVsApi client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    This is the single most useful thing to internalise: <strong>the model has no memory between calls.</strong> What
    looks like memory is just the transcript being replayed to it every turn. It is less like a colleague who remembers
    your last chat, and more like handing a brilliant stranger the full printout of your conversation so far and asking
    "what is the next line?"
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Input = context + prompt</h2>
  <p class="mb-6">
    That big input blob has two parts worth naming, because people muddle them constantly.
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>The prompt</strong> is your latest ask — the thing you just typed. "Add an email column."</li>
    <li>
      <strong>The context</strong> is everything else that gets bundled in around it: the hidden system prompt, any files
      or memory the tool pulls in (like a <code>CLAUDE.md</code>), results from tools the model ran, and every earlier
      message in the thread.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p class="mb-6">
    So your prompt is a small part of what the model actually reads. Most of the input is context you may not even be
    aware of. When the answer surprises you, the prompt is usually fine — it is the <em>context</em> that was off.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">It all shares one budget</h2>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Here is the catch. All of that — system prompt, tools, files, memory, every past message — has to fit inside one
    fixed space called the <strong>context window</strong>. Think of it as a single fixed-size box. Everything the model
    is allowed to "see" on this turn has to fit in the box, and the box does not grow.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    A real breakdown of that box looks roughly like this — the hidden instructions, the tool definitions, connected
    services, your memory files, and the actual conversation all carve out a slice before you have said a word:
  </p>

  <TokenBudget client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    The practical consequence: <strong>context is finite and contested, not free.</strong> Every file you ask the model
    to read, every tool call it makes, every long pasted log — all of it spends from the same budget. Fill the box with
    junk and there is less room for the model to actually think. This is why "just give it more context" is not the free
    win it sounds like.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Three inputs people mash together</h2>
  <p class="mb-6">
    When you give an LLM work, you are really handing it three different kinds of information. They shape the result in
    different ways, and mixing them up is one of the most common mistakes:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>
      <strong>Rules</strong> — the non-task-specific "how we work here" stuff. A <code>CLAUDE.md</code>, a style guide,
      conventions. This is stable; it should be true on every task.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Code / world state</strong> — the repo, the data, the system exactly as it is right now. This changes
      constantly and is specific to this moment.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The goal</strong> — what "done" means <em>this time</em>. The actual ask. This changes every task.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    code={`RULES         "Use snake_case. Write a migration for every schema change."   (always true)
WORLD STATE   the users table, as it exists in the repo right now              (true now)
GOAL          "Add an email column to that table."                            (true this task)`}
  />

  <p class="mb-6">
    Keep these straight and the model behaves. Blur them — bake a one-off goal into your permanent rules, or treat
    today's stale code dump as if it were the current state — and you get confident, wrong answers. A rule belongs in the
    rules; a goal belongs in the prompt; the world state should reflect reality, not last week's.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Why any of this matters</h2>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Once you see the model as input → output sharing one budget, the advice writes itself: <strong
      >what you put in is what shapes what comes out</strong
    >, and irrelevant or stale context actively degrades the result. More is not better. Two failure modes are worth
    knowing by name:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>
      <strong>Context rot</strong> — a rule you set early gets buried under dozens of later turns, and the model
      effectively forgets it. It was true at the top of the box; now it is drowned out.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Context pollution</strong> — semi-related material you dragged in (an old thread, a half-relevant file)
      quietly bends the answer toward the wrong thing.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p class="mb-6">
    That is the practical picture, and it is enough to use these tools well. If you want the deeper "why" — how the input
    actually shapes the space of possible outputs — that is the subject of <a
      class="text-primary hover:underline"
      href="/blog/probability-space-engineering">Probability Space Engineering</a
    >. And if you have noticed the model is brilliant one moment and baffled by something trivial the next, that is its
    own thing, covered in <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/jagged-intelligence">Jagged Intelligence</a
    >.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The whole thing in one breath</h2>
  <p class="mb-6">
    An LLM takes one text input and returns one text output, with no memory in between. The chat is just a view; every
    turn the whole transcript plus hidden instructions is re-sent from scratch. That input is <em>context + prompt</em>,
    and it all has to fit in one fixed budget — so what you choose to include, and what you leave out, is most of the
    skill. That is genuinely most of how this works under the hood.
  </p>

  <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground mb-3">Related</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-muted-foreground">
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/jagged-intelligence">Jagged Intelligence</a> — why LLMs are
        smart and bad at once
      </li>
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/probability-space-engineering">Probability Space Engineering</a
        > — the deeper model of how outputs are shaped
      </li>
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">Autonomous Agents</a> — putting it to work
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
